# Pre-Researcher — bowling-shirt-designer

Answering the 7 planner questions in priority order.

---

## Q1 [BLOCKER] — Free bowling/camp-collar shirt GLTF with separable materials + back UV

**Verdict: use procedural fallback — it is the correct choice, not a compromise.**

No freely downloadable, purpose-built bowling-shirt GLB with clean separable material groups and a flat back-panel UV reliably exists on Sketchfab/pmndrs market without manual mesh surgery. Searching Sketchfab for "bowling shirt" CC0/CC-BY yields generic polo or t-shirt meshes that need UV rework anyway.

**Procedural shirt (recommended) — 4 mesh groups:**
```
ShirtBody       BoxGeometry(1.0, 1.3, 0.2) + SphereGeometry shoulders — MeshStandardMaterial #0
Collar          TorusGeometry(0.22, 0.06) flat at top — MeshStandardMaterial #1
Sleeves         CylinderGeometry(0.15, 0.18, 0.45) x2 — MeshStandardMaterial #2
BackPanel       PlaneGeometry(0.7, 0.8) parented to ShirtBody, z-offset +0.101
                UV: 0→1 across the full plane — CanvasTexture writes directly here
```
Benefits: zero GLTF load risk, perfect back UV (flat plane = no distortion), 3 clearly named material indices for per-segment color, works within 3-min build budget. The shirt can be simplified/stylized to read "vintage bowling shirt" without photorealism.

If a real GLTF is preferred, check: `https://market.pmnd.rs/` (filter: clothing) and Sketchfab `https://sketchfab.com/search?q=polo+shirt&type=models&features=downloadable&licenses=322a749bcfa841b29dff1e8a1bb74b0b` (CC0 filter). Any download requires verifying it has distinct mesh groups or splitting in Blender before use — budget risk is real.

**Decision for demo-builder: use procedural mesh. Back panel = PlaneGeometry child, fully flat UV, CanvasTexture-ready.**

