## Q7 — drei `<Decal>` vs CanvasTexture for text-on-back

**Verdict: use `<Decal>` from `@react-three/drei` — it is the correct technique.**

Why Decal wins:
- Projects onto any surface without requiring clean flat UV (critical for a real GLTF; irrelevant but still clean for procedural mesh)
- Has `position`, `rotation`, `scale` props — allows interactive repositioning without UV rework
- Survives OrbitControls transforms natively (it is part of the scene graph)
- Mobile: works fine, no special handling

Correct pattern:
```jsx
// offscreen canvas → texture → Decal
const textCanvas = useMemo(() => {
  const c = document.createElement('canvas'); c.width=512; c.height=256;
  const ctx = c.getContext('2d');
  ctx.font = `bold ${fontSize}px ${fontFamily}`;
  ctx.fillStyle = textColor;
  ctx.textAlign = 'center';
  ctx.fillText(text, 256, 140);
  return c;
}, [text, fontSize, fontFamily, textColor]);

const textTexture = useMemo(() => {
  const t = new THREE.CanvasTexture(textCanvas);
  t.needsUpdate = true;
  return t;
}, [textCanvas]);

// Inside the shirt JSX:
<Decal
  position={[0, 0.1, -0.101]}   // back-center of shirt
  rotation={[0, Math.PI, 0]}
  scale={[0.5, 0.25, 1]}
  map={textTexture}
/>
```

Debounce text input at 150ms to avoid per-keystroke texture rebuild.

With procedural mesh (Q1 above), the BackPanel PlaneGeometry is an even simpler alternative: just update `backPanelMesh.material.map = textTexture; map.needsUpdate = true`. Either works; Decal is the r3f-idiomatic choice.

